VNote: Course conducted in English with all works available in English translation. Students with a high enough level of French will have the option of reading the works in the original French.\u000a\u000aFrom Pep le Pew to Robert Doisneau\u2019s iconic photograph of a couple kissing by Paris\u2019s Hotl de Ville (City Hall), the French have a privileged relationship to love and romance that few countries can rival: French is the language of love, Paris is the city of light and lovers, seduction is a French art, etc. And yet, for a culture that is so love-centric, the French love story rarely ends well. Indeed, French literature could be described as an enormous lonely hearts club, with one story of love and loss after another. In this seminar, we will retrace the long and venerable history of broken hearts, from the Middle Ages to today, and as we move from one ruined life to the next, we will be able to unpack such weighty and historically-contingent concepts as love, desire, morality, sexuality, gender, race, class, and how they transform and are transformed by writing. Authors read will include Madame de la Fayette, George Sand, Gustave Flaubert, Marcel Proust, and Marguerite Duras, among others. \u000aThere is no additional essay question for this seminar.\u000a
