VHealth and Mental Health in Everyday Life
p1684
sg9
VWhy do students feel ill before an exam? Why do women seem to suffer more than men from depression and eating disorders, whereas men use and abuse substances more than women? Why do some ethnic groups (Latinos, Asian Americans) live longer than other groups despite similar social conditions? These are some of the issues in health and mental health that this course investigates. Using interdisciplinary perspectives we will investigate how social and personal characteristics, such as gender, race/ethnicity, family background, and self-esteem impact health and mental health behaviors and outcomes. We will also examine the unique role of certain circumstances and contexts in contributing to health and mental health problems. For instance, college students, regardless of gender, race/ethnicity, etc., are increasingly experiencing stress and turning to amphetamines at higher rates than young adults who are not in college. Our goal in these classes will be to explore various coping and healing strategies and the roles of individuals themselves, their personal and social support networks, and health care professionals in guiding positive health and mental health change. Throughout, we traverse the boundary between health and illness in order to understand the complex web of factors that create and jeopardize well-being. Students will present analyses of the readings in class and write short papers based on class readings and discussions. One paper will include additional research. Students will also give two brief presentations: a team project and a representation of gender, health and mental health in the arts.\u000a\u000aThere is no additional essay question for this seminar.
