VOne World, 1943: Or, How Americans Discovered the World
p1841
sg9
VIn late summer of 1942, with World War II raging around the globe, US President Franklin D. Roosevelt sent his erstwhile Republican opponent in the election of 1940, Wendell L. Willkie, on a forty-nine-day trip around the world.  On October 26, twelve days after landing back on US soil, Willkie made a \u201cReport to the People,\u201d a radio address describing his experiences that was heard by some 36 million people. About six months later, in April 1943, Willkie published a travelogue, One World, that sold millions of copies, topping the New York Times bestseller list for the next four months. That book, since largely forgotten, will serve as the launching pad of our explorations in this seminar. Each week, we will read a section of this book, taking us through Willkie\u2019s itinerary and experiences on his world tour, starting with North Africa and passing through various stops in the Middle East, Russia, Central Asia, China, Siberia, and back home.\u000aThere is no additional essay question for this seminar.
